i am not very sure about what openings are called but i do know how to play so here is my annotate...... As always i start out with d4 or c4 to play the English opening but in this case i did d4
Black responds with Nf6 standard move played by black
regardless of blacks first move i usually follow up d4 with c4 unless black plays c5 which people have done in some occasions
A gambit by black so he can be able to develop his pieces faster if i decide to take e5

The reason i decide to do Dxe5 is because i know in the long run he will be able to get e5 back if he is indeed a good player but because i dont really like pushing d4 to d5 or play e3 to exchange pawns
Usually some people would play Ng4 to attack e pawn which if i defend with Nf3 the opponent then usually plays Nc6 but in this case my opponent plays Ne4
I decide to push my e pawn in this game to protect my c pawn from attacks further along in the game
Bd2 seem the best option in this case
Now my opponent attacks my e pawn
I defend as usual with Nf3 but i know in the long run that its pointless to defend that pawn much further
Attacking the e pawn as suspected

Making him force to take the knight.... Ba5 or Bc5 leads to him losing the Bishop... although i had thought about this beforehand if my opponent had decide to play Bc5 i would push my pawn from b2 to b4 attacking bishop but i was afraid if he took e3 weakening my king side i would be up plus 2 but both my king side and queen side are both heavily damaged.... After Bxe3 fxe3 Nxe5 i feel i am under a lot of pressure although my opponent doesn't have any other develop pieces
As i hoped
recapturing with the Knight wasn't very appealing because of the b2 pawn
taking back the pawn which he sacrificed earlier
I feel i needed to castle at some point
just so my opponent couldn't push the b pawn and puts my Bishop in a better position than it was

I couldn't play Bxb7 because of Rah8 if i defend with Qb4 then my opponent wins a piece by playing Bc6 if i decide to take the pawn and move my bishop back to f3 after my opponent plays Rab8 i lose the B2 pawn and my queen is under attack while having a weak c4 pawn
so i play b4 if my opponent misses the move of Bxb7 i win a pawn
here i was wondering why have double pawns in the c file of course Rab8 was something i may have played maybe not but i took the Bishop thinking i had a better set-up....
i wasn't really sure what to do here so decided that i don't want him to push d6

this move here a7 to a5 i decided that this will determine whether i win or lose not sure what was going through my mind but i wanted queens off the board rather than Bxa5 which weakens both my c pawn and a pawn
now any mistake could lose either of use the game
i knew i could defend the b4 pawn that's why i let him take....
if my opponent decides to take c5 with his pawn i reply back with bxc5 and if my opponent swaps off rooks i knew i am in a better advantage because he has two double pawns in the c file
my opponent replies with d5 which i feel gave me the advantage here
maybe e4 would of been better in this case
putting my b pawn under pressure but not so much
was preparing for e4 and releasing my King from a back-rank checkmate
I got lucky because my opponent made a blunder the mistake which should have won me the game
If my opponent decides to take back with cxd5 i can take with my rook which u will see shortly
this move wins me the c pawn regardless of what my opponent does next move
Now i am a pawn up and i should of closed this game out better
i was hoping at this point that his king would go to d6 so i could collect his g pawn or h pawn by playing Rg8
i was hoping for Kd7 so i could win the h8 pawn and still be a pawn up

when this move happen i missed the next move which should of been Rh7 because the c7 pawn was already lost unless my opponent made a huge error... if i played Rh8 my opponent had to take pawn because i would promote next move leaving me to take the h pawn
i realized too late that i could take the h pawn
as to prevent Rh7
wasn't sure what was going through my mind I was playing poker at the same time and was rushing my moves thinking i had it won
My next move cost me the win
i wasn't paying attention and after i made the move i new that i was most likely going to draw this game
now i was hoping for a mistake by my opponent
If my opponent took on h4 i would reply by taking the g5 pawn and trapping the King on h4
smart move by black
here i was just thinking of taking the draw but something in my mind said to give it one more shot
was hoping for a mistake which may come later
i was attempting to play Kh3 if i played that last move his rook could of went to c1 threatening a checkmate on h1
playing this first just incase i need to check on the a file
i went through this in my head so many times thinking that i have won the game but i forgot my opponent could play fxg3
have to move the King to e or f6 to play g4
i thought that he had to play hxg4 forgetting about enpassat if my opponent play hxg4 white would win the game by playing Kxg4 threatening his f pawn which would inevitable be lost
here i realized that it would be a draw kicking myself because i should of won if not for the mistake on move 32
In all it was a very good game and my opponent played a better end game than i.........

My standard first move. Many people I'm sure will give this a ?! as it does nothing for my development or the centre. However I prefer black's opening setups to white's and 1. a3 not only allows me to adopt those but sometimes it can be useful.
A sort of latvian gambit with the colours reversed. Although not entirely sound it often makes for an exiting game!
This move throws away any possible advantage for black. Black's dark squared bishop is blocked in and I am given the chance to defend my centre. Better was 3. ...Nxe4
Another odd move from black. He develops his knight to a slightly passive square while blocking in his light squared bishop. I would prefer 4. ...Be7.
Simple development. Because black has blocked his light squared bishop he can no longer pin my knight with Bg4 (which would make my pressure against e5 slightly weaker).

I felt that Bc4 would expose my bishop to a future a6 and b5 (I move my bishop probably to a2) followed by Bb7 when black has a very strong bishop on the long diagonal and a lot of queenside space and potential counterplay. However I needed to get castled before black could stop me by placing his queen or bishop on the a7-g1 diagonal.
This move prepares the d5 break and also gives the black queen space. Black's formation is slightly passive but very solid so it is hard for me to damage his position.
Qb6 was threatened when I would have to waste a few moves getting the black queen off the a7-g1 diagonal before I could castle.
This move is a bit of a waste of time as although it protects against 8. Ng5 I would then have no good followup. One man is not an army as they say.
I prepare to activate my bishop whilst further solidifying my centre.
This move prevents any future tactics on the a7-g1 diagonal whilst also preeing up the g1 square for my rook if I ever need it there in a kingside attack.
Black had to move the knight eventually to get his bishop out.
Gives the queen more options. Moving it to the kingside looks likely.
My dark squared bishop is now very active and currently discourages the d5 break.

A very serious error. Although there is no immediate tactical response this gives me the kingside weaknesses (in particular the h5-e8 diagonal which can no longer be defended with g6) that I need to damage his position. Note how the light squares become very weak for black after he exchanges his bishop.
12. Bg3 would expose the bishop to a potential kingside pawn avalanche which would justify the g5 advance.
Opens up the f-file and prepares to take advantage of the f5 weakness also created by the g5 push.
A wasted move. I was threatening very little on the queenside and if it was to support a queenside push then it is still too slow to be of much use.
My knight is very powerful on this square and attacks many kingside and central squares.
Black naturally eliminates my strong knight but at a high price: his light squared bishop. Now the kingside light square weaknesses have no defender and my queen and bishop invade.
prevents the d5 push (black's only real chance of counterplay) and adds to the kingside pressure.
Yet another serious error. This hopes to neutralise the pressure on the f-file but weakens the h5-e8 diagonal.
Now I have pressure on the h3-c8 diagonal too. The black king is caught between them.
I begin kicking black's knights around to improve my position.
I now have more space and I now take away the b6 square to remove it as an option for black's queen and also to get a potential outpost
I wanted to get my knight to f5 but in the game this doesnt happen as the d5 spot becomes available.
I am not giving up a pawn here. My central control prevents black holding onto it for long.
An excellent outpost for my knight. Black is severely lacking coordination now.
My pieces are now all active (except the a1 rook but that can be quickli added to an attack if needed) and I am ready to go for the kill.
A mistake but things are bad for black now anyway.
The start of the winning combination. Note that I use primarily the light squares to invade on because they are very weak. The discoordinated knights can't defend them effectively.
Black has to give up control of the e6 square now.

Now the black king is in obvious danger. I have invaded the light squares as best I can now so I precede to finish him off on the dark squares which inevitably are not well defended after black has been focused on defending threats on their light counterparts.
I was threatening Nxf6+
If 35. ...Nxg6 then 36. Nxf6 destroys black's last defences and his position is hopeless.
Well what else? I could now take the queen and have a crushing material advantage but I prefer the quick kill.
!! Black finally falls on the dark squares. It turns out that the f6 barrier was in fact not strong enough to keep the f-file closed.
Now if 37. ...Kg8 then white plays Ne7+ and black must give up his queen.
Black can't avoid mate in a few moves now. I think after black moves I will have at least a mate in 6 but could people please verify this.
Now black is forced to give up his queen.
Now black resigned. After 40. ...Ke8 I will have a mate in 3. Thanks for reading please leave a comment!! :-)

Here shows the danger of the Lolli attack. My opponent blundered but my attack was still going to be quite strong and he discovered that this Lolli wasn't very sweet.
I decided to play the Italian game. While considered toothless it still has some dangerous lines if black isn't prepared for them. It however has been overshadowed by it's big brother the Ruy Lopez.
Two Knights Not seen much over the board because black needs to be quite accurate in his defence however common in correspondence.

following Cramling Pia - Cmilyte Viktorija Elista 2004 1/2-1/2

and black diverged from Cramling-Cmilyte... he probably intends to block my pawns with c4-b3 next so if I want to keep the position dynamic I need to exchange dxc5 or push the c pawn or get my knight to e5 with the idea of playing some tactics with Nxc4-Bxb7...

now I'll do some exchanges to avoid having my queen side closed by black's pawns advance...

a little trap because if  black plays the seemingly natural c4 to execute the queen side block plan he then would face the loss of a piece with Nxf6+ with tempo and them I simply move the queen away from d4
he didn't fall for that trap and now we have cxb4 cxb4 and then Nd2 or Bg5...
development Nd2-b3 eyeing both a5 and c5
to challenge the dark squares and offer the exchange of black's best bishop...
wisely refuses the exchange and improves his light squared bishop
now I invite Bxc5 dxc5 and after this I'll have a passed yet unprotected c pawn
I now have the bishop pair and a passed pawn

avoids a probable center pawns push with tempo by black if I would have played Qe3 also allows me to push e4 at any time and at the same time invites black to go in to the line Ne4 Bxe4 dxe4 and then either to exchange queens or to place the dark squares bishop on d6 supporting c5 and at the same time in a nice attacking outpost... e expect black to prepare Ne4 with Rd8 due to the threat Qxd7

The Sicilian is often seen at master level. It can lead to very sharp play as explained in some other annotations of mine. I normally see 1...e5 in my games.

A somewhat non-committal move as Black can still choose from many Sicilian systems such as the Scheveningen the Taimanov and the Kan variation. Nevertheless 2...d6 is more often seen which can lead to the hyper-sharp Najdorf and dragon variations. Another possibility is 2...Nc6 which can lead to the accelerated dragon and the Sveshnikov. (Other transpositions are also possible) Another advantage of this move is that it discourages 3.Bb5 as after 3...a6! the bishop has to retreat because 4.Ba4?? b5 5.Bb3 c4 loses it. This move (3.Bb5) is a good possibility against 2...d6 and 2...Nc6 though.
I stick with what I know - the open Sicilians.
The Kan variation - a rock solid approach but it can have quite some 'bite' if either player is not careful.

Black chooses to expand early on the queenside without even developing a piece. This is the so-called minority attack: Black has a 3 vs. 2 minority on the queenside so if two pairs of pawns are exchanged white is left with an isolated pawn on that side of the board which can be attacked easily by the open lines that are created.
Black also wants to control a small share of the centre though White hasmore control on that part of the board for now.

I keep making solid developing moves. In many variations of the Sicilian I like to castle queenside but as Black already has an attack going at that side (and to be honest another reason was that I was playing a master) I chose the safer approach.
This move is rarely seen. Far more common are 7...Nf6 and 7...Bb7.

Trying to induce Black's pawns forward to be able to attack them and break them up. The immediate threat is 9.axb5 on which Black can't respond 9...axb5?? on account of the hanging rook on a8. I was aware of the fact that I followed a game in the database which ended in a win for Black and I knew that I would probably have to deviate to hope for a better result than in that game.

But to my delight the master deviates first. The move played in the game we followed 8...bxa4 looks somewhat illogical as it isolates the a pawn which can be attacked easily as it is on an open file after White retakes.

Attacking the pawn. Other squares are even worse: 9.Nde2 blocks a good developing square for the queen and on b1 the knight is nothing but a spectator as a3 and c3 are both controlled by the pawn on b4 and there doesn't seem to be a nice spot which the knight can go to in the near future. Also it blocks the rook from developing so it has to move again soon (after the bishop and queen are out). That combined with what I saw in games in the opening DB and with earlier experience in this variation (not this particular position) were the reasons why I preferred this move.

? Normally I would hesitate to give a move made by a master a ? but as the master admitted this move was a plain oversight. Ion had written the notation down wrongly so he had the wrong position on the board. As he didn't look at the board on the GK site properly he made this blunder... Fortunately for him it was only a pawn that I could win.

! This simple knight fork (with double attack on b4) wins me a pawn. I was really hesitating to make this move as I was afraid the master had set a trap which I was not aware of but I couldn't find a reason not to play it so I decided I would try and see what would happen.

At first I wanted to play 11.Naxb4?? until I discovered that that would be a horrible blunder as 11...a5 wins a piece (the knights can't defend each other anymore). The computer gives me a decisive edge (+1.91) at this point while Ion felt that he had some compensation in an active game and open lines for his pieces now. I'm not sure who is right or wrong as I felt I also had active piece play and especially a strong grip on the centre so I thought my advantage was at least a clear pawn.
Developing with tempo but my advantage drops slightly to +1.51. I'm not sure what is wrong with this though...

I would expect the bishop to develop to this spot but if the queen would go to a5/d8 or c7 there could be some tactics involving knight forks on c6 or d5 respectively and on b8 she blocks the natural square for the rook.

!? Gaining space in the centre and preparing a kingside assault as is often the plan in the Sicilian for White. However Black's position has no weaknesses at that side of the board (which is often the case in the Kan) and maybe I should have switched my attention to the queenside in particular the weak a6 pawn (but 13.Qe2 would be strongly met with 13...Nc5 when I have to concede the bishop pair because 14.Bc4 loses the a pawn).

There are many options here but I decided to make a waiting move to see what Black would do. Another move I considered was 14.Qe2 but I didn't like to concede the bishop pair after 14...Nc5. Still it could be a good move as after (14.Qe2 Nc5) 15.Bxc5 dxc5 Black has many weaknesses on the queenside.

Opening lines on the kingside. Though the computer doesn't spot an inaccuracy my advantage decreases by 0.3 or 0.4 points with every move I make and has now fallen to only +0.45 (while I still had the feeling that I was far better if not winning though I knew who I was playing against).

?? And here I make a horrible blunder. I had probably forgotten that the exchange on e5 had also opened a line for Black... My idea of course was an attack on the f file and f7 in partiicular but that didn't quite happen.

? The mistakes keep coming. Here I simply forgot about the e pawn. In an OTB game it is quite normal to make two mistakes in a row due to the psychological effect but it's not necessary in a correspondence game. My idea was to place a rook on e1 of course.
Dreaming about exchange sacs on f6 (why not? I'm way behind in material so might as well throw in some extra wood).
? Planning to double on the f file but this is another blunder.
The game is totally over now.
I could have tried 20.Bd3 but I had the idea to win back some material on d7...
However by neglecting my defence I allow Ion to mate me with a nice piece sac.
! It's mate in 6.
It's mate in 2 now. 24.Kg3 would last a little bit longer but I missed that after 24...Bf2+ I could return to g2: 25.Kg2 Be1+! (necessary to block the 8th row) 26.Kg1 Qf2+ 27.Kh1 Qf1#.

A convincing win for the master but I had a good game until my blunder at move 16. Thanks for reading I'd like to receive some comments. Ion thanks for this lesson I hope we can play another game soon.

The following game is a variation of the Ruy Lopez that I enjoyed because it demonstrates how delaying the castle allows white to gain piecemeal advantage. This game would not be at masters level.. my rate fluctuates from 1480 to 1540. So this is game played at the mid 1550 level.
This move is a mistake. Black expects one of two things; either O-O-O or Bxc6+. However this move is not prepared to meet d4 w/o losing a pawn
Black could chose cx4 but that would be worse than a6. White could respond to cx4 with Ncx4 which wins white development. F6 would be even worse because it blocks black's knight from moving ou.
I don't agree with this move. The sequence it inaugurates ends badly for black. I would chose Qe7.. with the plan of Bg3 to pin white's knight and then rd8 to exploit the opening in the pawn line.

White is up a point but is winning the opening decisively. Black's knight cannot move out anywhere safely the bishop on f8 is trapped as well. It will be very hard from here on out for black to castle. Black makes the best choice possible on this situation to try and regain momentum.
Bg4 links the queen and the rock which would free up black to take the e5 pawn and even out material. This will work but it allows white to develop faster.

I don't agree with this bishop aggression. Bg4 is better because the bishop is defended by the rook black doesn't have to keep moving it. It also allows white to move Bf4 b/c the rook isn't threatened.
Erasing the material deficit just became much more difficult.
I don't agree with this move.. there is nowhere the knight can productively go from e7. Black moves it because he needs to castle but I think moving the g6 then black's Bh6 is a better choice.
White has several options at this point.. Nd2 might have been a more prudent choice than moving the queen out.
This move is a waste. The rook will end up on the d column once black initiates the queen trade.
the exchange is on.
I could have taken with the bishop to menace the c7 pawn... but I've learned from experience that is very bad if BxNf4 gx3 because it disrupts the king's defenses.
A mistake. Forcing Re1 is good for white the rook has to move out eventually and re1 protects the e4 pawn.
Baiting the back rank checkmate. I would chose a more aggressive move Ng6 comes to mind. It would also free up the bishop and finally allow black to castle.
Retreats
This prevents the castling for an additional move and allows white to retake control of the center.
Only possible response for black.

I would have delayed the castling to meet Nc5. Although I cannot see a move here that prevents Nc5. Also look how long it takes black to castle! The stage of black's development lags considerably behind white's.
I'm not sure why Be2.. the rook is going to move up the field anyway. Be2 does not stop Rd7 which is where white will snipe a pawn.
Black's knight is anchored to e7 in order to defend the c6 pawn. He has to defend it with either the rook or the bishop. He chooses the bishop I think was a mistake b/c the bishop is unsupported.
Is Rd8 a threat to white?
Short answer... no.
In the event of a rook trade I didn't want the bishop to be in a position to wreck havoc on my pawns. It also baits a trap... the only safe move for the bishop is Bh6. Bb5 leads to disaster.
Retreat is blocked by the knight.
Motivated more by desperation than strategy.
Black has to respond to the imminent lose of his bishop or his rook.

White continues to accumulate material advantage. In this kind of position I prefer to slowly accumulate a material lead instead of attempting a quick kill. That's not quite how it worked out here though.
supports the bishop so the knight can move around again.

Ne7 is a disaster... where can the knight move from here? what kind of attack can it support? Also it prevents the rook from being able to defend the against rd8#.. which is coming. From here.. Nc5 presents black with a terrible choice.. lose the rook or be checkmated.
Opting for the latter course of action.

There are several key points in this game. 1. d4 is difficult to meet in the Ruy Lopez. 2. Don't overmove periphery pieces when you need to develop your castling position. 3. Force a piece to move where it natural wants to go is not pressure. 4. Don't isolate the rook from the back rank unless the king is well defended.

This game begins on the well-trodden path of the Ruy Lopez. But delving into a lesser known variation White makes a risky move that triggers a violent attack against his own king.
White's set-up has been played before and aims to clamp down on any future Black hopes of the freeing advance of his d-pawn to d5.

So what is there for Black to do? His opponent has an excellent grip on the light squares and has left Black very little room to manoeuvre. There will be a bit more space if a piece is traded. After that; Black has a set-up which indicates that he should aim to play f7-f5.
There is no way to be sure that this is correct. Nevertheless it looks a bit more active than other knight moves - and it is also a little provocative.

[?!] White is a strong player and experience would have told him that this sort of pawn advance in front of a king can be risky. On the other hand; there appears no particular danger at this point and - when the knight retreats - he will have  made Black's idea of f7-f5 even more problematic.

[!] But now there is a problem: Black relies on the weakened king's position and is determined to create counter-play - even at the cost of a piece. I felt that at worst I could probably escape with a perpetual check if things did not 'work out'.
The obvious move was to play 13...Bxh3. But there is really no rush and the top priority is to open the f-file and add the rook to the attack.

[!] Taking my life in my hands here to some extent - but in fact this is stronger than moving the bishop. Anything else will allow White to play either f2-f4 or f2-f3 and organize a defence involving moves such as Rf2 and Qf1 for example.

The best move: If White takes the bishop then he has to reckon on ...Rf3 which blocks his f-pawn. After that Black now has three attackers [counting his c8 bishop] the white h-pawn is still en prise and there are  potential mating threats against both g2 and h1.
I couldn't think of anything better than to start the threats.
I am not completely sure that this position is lost for White - but despite being two pieces up; it is obviously going to be difficult to defend.
I think it was essential to return some material here and play either Nf4 or Bf4 and hope for the best.
The pawn is captured so as to add Black's last piece to the attack.
With the idea of exchanging queens - even with Qh6.
side-stepping White's plans to simplify.
Note that now Black is threatening Rxg3 followed by Rxf1. So White moves the rook away.

[!!] This is the end: White has a few checks true: But my opponent knows that all they achieve is to remove his queen from the defence of g2. If White plays Rg1 here then the response is the final sacrifice ...Bg2+!! with a quick mate after either capture.

I understand the logic behind this move because Jack Stockel told me that it is not a good idea to capture the knight after a pawn move breaks the pin.  However I recently learned from inadowman that it would have been perfectly ok to make the capture.

Since he does not make the capture I do not know what to do now so I decide to take a risk.  I recently learned that you have to take some risks in chess.  Therefore I chose this candidate to "box in" his d pawn because I thought that it was a threat.  I originally believed that I would be a little behind with a -3 at worst but it was much then that.  Instead it turns out to be a very serious blunder so it was ??.  In fact the game is now lost.  I will explain this later on.
In this position I cannot capture the knight with Nxd4 or I will immediately loose the queen since my knight on f3 still pinned.
Therefore I made this move to threaten the queen with Bxd8.  I decided to take another risk because I was hoping that he would not spot this threat but he sees it.
As a result he chose this candidate to protect his queen on d8.
Consequently I am now forced to retreat my bishop.

Therefore I am now forced to take with the pawn so I now have two bad f pawns.  Most importantly my king is now exposed so there is no way out of trouble in this position.  However I do not want to resign yet because I am still hoping that I could come up with something good but that will not happen.
He made this move because he wants a free h pawn but I am not about to allow that.
Therefore I respond by capturing his bishop and I thought that he would recapture the bishop with dxc5.  However that will not happen.

Instead is much worse then that because he captures my pawn.  Even though I am two pieces ahead with a +2 the game is inevitably lost.  That is because he will win my queen at best and mate me at worst.  In fact he will be able to find a mating pattern against me in this position and it is inevitable.  Therefore I resign at this point.  10.Nd5 was the mistake because it caused my king to become exposed.  This shows that one blunder could win or loose a game.

White's aggressive opening move opens lines for the queen and king's bishop and fights for control of the squares d5 and f5.

Black plays the classical response to 1. e4. By mirroring White's move Black has guaranteed himself an equal share of the centre and scope to develop his pieces. 1...e5 is one of the few moves that directly interferes with White's plan of playing d4.

Is the natural move combining defence of the pawn with control of the d4 square and refusing to commit another pawn. The extent of this move's popularity is such that the typical player of 2. Nf3 as White is already thinking beyond it to their third move safe in the knowledge that any variation by Black will play into their hands.

White has multiple choices here which can lead to very different games. 3. Bb5 (Ruy Lopez) is the most played. White puts pressure on the knight defending the pawn. I was thinking of 3. d4 (Scotch) because my opponent wanted a "Fast correspondence game" and 3. d4 is aggressive but decided against it as I have not played it in a very long time...not seriously anyways...

Enter the Ruy Lopez. White threatens to trade the bishop against the knight leaving the pawn undefended. It is not a real threat as after 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nxe5 Black can fork the knight and a pawn with 5...Qd4 or 5...Qg5. As nothing's urgent Black can respond in a variety of ways. The most common move is the Morphy defence : 3...a6 forcing White to make a decision about his bishop. Many other moves are available some neglecting completely the protection of the knight and the pawn and continuing development.

 I assumed he would choose a route that would let us really open of the center...

After this move my opponent said that he was finished with this game by resigning. That being said White played the Ruy Lopez as if he had little experience with it. It is one of the very few openings that require a lot of study time before you perform it. Also look everywhere. Sometimes I sit there looking at and studying a position for more than ten minutes to examine what I would need to do. If you're behind in points start defending; if you're ahead in points you can do more attacking. No matter where you stand in your games you need to act as if no one is winning so that you don't hurry and mess up on your tactics.

As a result I inadvertently give away a free rook.  Consequently I am far behind at -13 and she has an inevitable mating pattern against me.  That is because she will be able to mate me as soon as she is able to play Qxf1#.   Therefore I resign because I do not "stand a chance" here.  It is not a good idea  not to make a move just because it seems good.  After all "don't judge a book by its cover" as they say.  Instead it is important to answer the "why" questions in chess.  That is because you do not know if a move is good unless you know the logic behind you know what makes the move good or bad.

That's the game. Black's critical mistakes began when he unnecessarily checked me with the Bishop. Then when his Queen was doing nothing on a5 he could have moved it in the sense that something bad was going to happen. Alsothe openings are always on proper development (well almost always) and use what you have even if you are down material. Finally when you're down material you are forced to defend your position. What you do in the opening will affect you in the mid-game; what you do in the mid-game will affect you in the endgame and what you do then will affect the results. Chess is a colossal chain reaction and you better be careful about your moves. This is why you need to look at your move before comfirming it.

Hi everyone!

At least I have had some success in the Love Conquers All MT.  This game was against a Class C player called Paul.  When I first played him after joining The Coaching Club (now alas extinct) my rating was similar to his - we were both rated in the 1520s.  A lot has happened since then.  So how did I win this?  Well after kicking off with 1. e4 and my opponent responding with the Nimzowich Defense (named after GM Aeron Nimzowich) here is the Gameknot Analysis:- http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=17043614&rnd=0.8169159996991752
3. Nc3 - I decided to open up lines for both my ecclesiastical twins and follow up with developing a knight.
4. e5 - transposing into an Alekhine's Defense - this is where black responds with 1..... Nf6 after e4.
6. Nf3 - after this pawn wedge I get on with developing my pieces.
8. Qxf3 - I am glad that Paul decided to swap off his lsb.  That piece can be a nuisance.  Glenda is on a good square she is putting pressure on d5 and indirect pressure on f7 until black castles.
10. ..... bxc6 - I return the compliment by trading off my own lsb for a knight.  Although it does give a clear line for black's QR it does make the a pawn a weakie.
14. Ne2 - I am thinking about re-deploying my knight to g3 where I can perhaps tempt the Wicked Witch of the West to go to h4 and give her a very nasty discovery.
16. Rad1 - lining my rook onto the same file as the Witch.

17. Nxg3 - black wisely trades knights.  That knight was looking good on f5 and I wanted to either exchange it or drive it to a more passive square.  Glenda decides to recapture as she gets a decent view of g7.
19. Qh3 - the start of a subtle shuffle takes place.
20. Bh4 - Step 1 - I gain a tempo by attacking the Wicked Witch of the West.
21. Qg3 - Step 2- Glenda ends up doing the Timewarp in reverse with a jump to the left as she has already done her step to the right.  Next up is Bf6 taking advantage of the pin on g7.
21. ..... g6?? - Step 3 - my opponent obliges by moving up his g pawn.  Kh8 would have at least got out of the pin without weakening his position.

22. ..... c5 - black tries to cause trouble on the queenside by menacing my d4 pawn.  With Step 4 Glenda jumps to g5 and now threatens Qh6 then Qg7#.  Yup the BK will cop Old Matey with the kiss of death.  Paul was aware of this and resigned on the grounds of Unavoidable Mate.  After being on the receiving end of two successful mating attacks by my master buddies myself I am glad to be the giver this time round!
